            <div type="glosses" subtype="textual">
                <note xml:id="TRANSPOSITIONGLOSS"><p><hi rend="bold">Lines 8&#x2013;9, transposition (MS VIII)&#x2014;</hi><persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> composed lines 8 and 9 in the order shown here, 
                    but then transposed the lines as indicated by the addition of a numeral 1 in front of line 9, and of a numeral 2 in front of line 8.</p></note>
                
                <note xml:id="SUBSTITUTIONGLOSS"><p><hi rend="bold">Line 43, substitution (MS VIII)&#x2014;</hi>In the left and right margin, 
                    line 43 is bracketed as if by large parentheses. Presumably, since the marks are in pencil like the other insertions by <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s father, <persName corresp="#JJR">John James</persName>, in this draft, 
                    then it was he also who was responsible for these marks. Unlike other substitutions prompted by <persName corresp="#JJR">John James</persName> in this draft, 
                    this revision is not confirmed by <persName corresp="#JR">John</persName>&#x02BC;s overwriting in ink; however, the substitution did ultimately become incorporated in a version of this line for the published version 
                    <title type="annual" corresp="FRIENDSHIPSOFFERING"><hi rend="italic">Friendship&#x02BC;s Offering</hi></title>. 
                    As the published version makes clear, <persName corresp="#JJR">John James</persName>&#x02BC;s <hi rend="italic">while</hi> should substitute for the phrase, <hi rend="italic">The weaker</hi>, and not just for one word, <hi rend="italic">weaker</hi>.</p></note>
            </div>
